				<h2>Using IR LED and photodiode to estimate range and bearing of other Swarm Robots</h2>
<p>I'm trying to make swarm robots that use 8 IR LEDs and 8 Photodiodes arranged alternately along the circumference of the circular body to determine the range and bearing of other nearby swarm robots (similar ro Rice University's <a href="http://mrsl.rice.edu/projects/r-one" rel="nofollow noreferrer">r-one</a>)</p>

<p>Each IR LED and Photodiode is wired as shown below:</p>

<p><a href="https://i.stack.imgur.com/HJKz0.png" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.stack.imgur.com/HJKz0.png" alt=""></a></p>

<p>The IR LED's and Photo-diodes on one robot are separated by some opaque object. The intention is that when a high analog value is read from certain Photo-diode(s) of the 8 present, another robot's relative range and bearing can be estimated.</p>

<p>The problem is that a high analog value is read even when the robot is near an obstacle because of the reflect infrared light from it's own LED's.</p>

<p>Is there any way for a robot to determine if a high analog value read is because of another robot or because of an obstacle?</p>

<p>Thanks in advance!</p>

