				<p><p>One way for a robot to determine if the light detected by a photodiode is from another robot, or from itself reflected off an obstacle, is to blink the LEDs in a pattern.</p>

<p>A blink detected by a robot when all of its own LEDs are turned off must have come from some other robot.</p>

<p>There are <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gold_code" rel="nofollow noreferrer">ways of designing a set of blink patterns</a>, encoding a unique ID number in each pattern, such that, even with a simple binary sensor that only distinguishes between "at least one robot has its LED turned on" vs "none of the robots in range have any LEDs turned on, not even me", it's possible to not only detect that some other robot is in range, but also the unique ID numbers of which specific other robots are in range.
You might find it interesting to give each specific LED its own blink pattern, so that you can detect which specific LEDs of your own and other robots are in range of some specific photodiode.</p>
</p><br>
